Performance estimation¶

Estimate the performance of each model using nested cross validation. Use 10-fold cross validation for outer and 5-fold repeated cross validation with 3 repetitions for inner loop.

Select the best model in the inner loop using the hyperparameter combinations and ranges defined in the Part 2. For each model, calculate the accuracy and the confusion matrix.

Which hyperparameter/hyperparameter combination is most often chosen as the best one for each classifier?

In [5]:
# initialize cross-validation methods
cv_inner = RepeatedKFold(n_splits=5, n_repeats=3, random_state=42)
cv_outer = KFold(n_splits=10, shuffle=True, random_state=1)

KNN¶

In [6]:
# parameter space
parameters={'n_neighbors': range(1,30)}
In [7]:
def KNNnestedCrossValidation():
    # initialize arrays to store calculated values
    best_params = []
    accuracy_scores = []
    confusion_matrices = []
    
    #loop through the splits made by the outer cross validation method
    for train_index, test_index in tqdm(cv_outer.split(features), total=10):
        
        # make data frames based on split indexes
        train_features, test_features = features.iloc[train_index], features.iloc[test_index]
        train_labels, test_labels = labels.iloc[train_index], labels.iloc[test_index]

        
        knn_model = KNeighborsClassifier()# initialize model
        knn_cv = GridSearchCV(knn_model, parameters, cv=cv_inner, return_train_score=False) # cross validation 
        fit = knn_cv.fit(train_features, train_labels) #fit with training data
        
        # get best values and add to array 
        best_params.append(knn_cv.best_params_['n_neighbors']) # get best parametes
        best_model = fit.best_estimator_ # fit model with best parameters
        predictions = best_model.predict(test_features) # make prediction on the best model
        accuracy_scores.append(accuracy_score(test_labels, predictions)) # accuracy score on the best model
        confusion_matrices.append(metrics.confusion_matrix(test_labels, predictions, labels=best_model.classes_)) #confusion martrix on the best model
        
    return best_params, accuracy_scores, confusion_matrices, best_model.classes_

def RFnestedCrossValidation():
    best_params = []
    accuracy_scores = []
    confusion_matrices = []
    
    for train_index, test_index in tqdm(cv_outer.split(features), total=10):

        train_features, test_features = features.iloc[train_index], features.iloc[test_index]
        train_labels, test_labels = labels.iloc[train_index], labels.iloc[test_index]

        rf_model = RandomForestClassifier()
        rf_cv = GridSearchCV(rf_model, parameters, cv=cv_inner, return_train_score=False, n_jobs=-1) #n_jobs=1 to use more of computer cappacity -> makes runing program baster (without this one iteration was about 70s now 30s) 
        fit = rf_cv.fit(train_features, train_labels)
        
        params = [rf_cv.best_params_['max_depth'], rf_cv.best_params_['max_features']]
        best_params.append(params)
        best_model = fit.best_estimator_
        
        predictions = best_model.predict(test_features)
        accuracy_scores.append(accuracy_score(test_labels, predictions))
        
        confusion_matrices.append(metrics.confusion_matrix(test_labels, predictions, labels=best_model.classes_))
        
    return best_params, accuracy_scores, confusion_matrices, best_model.classes_

In [20]:
def MLPnestedCrossValidation():
    best_params = []
    accuracy_scores = []
    confusion_matrices = []
    
    for train_index, test_index in tqdm(cv_outer.split(features), total=10):

        train_features, test_features = features.iloc[train_index], features.iloc[test_index]
        train_labels, test_labels = labels.iloc[train_index], labels.iloc[test_index]

        mlp_cv = GridSearchCV(mlp_model, parameters, cv=cv_inner, return_train_score=False, n_jobs=-1)
        fit = mlp_cv.fit(train_features.values, train_labels)
        
        params = [mlp_cv.best_params_['hidden_layer_sizes'], mlp_cv.best_params_['activation'], mlp_cv.best_params_['solver'], mlp_cv.best_params_['validation_fraction']]
        best_params.append(params)
        best_model = fit.best_estimator_
        
        predictions = best_model.predict(test_features)
        accuracy_scores.append(accuracy_score(test_labels, predictions))
        
        confusion_matrices.append(metrics.confusion_matrix(test_labels, predictions, labels=best_model.classes_))
        
    return best_params, accuracy_scores, confusion_matrices, best_model.classes_

Introduction¶

Write an introductory chapter for your report

Explain what is the purpose of this task?¶

The purpose is to reduce image data to numeric representation of the rice grains morphological and shape features that can be used to find the best model for classifying different types of rice grains. We use tree different types of rice: Arborio, Basmati and Jasmine. The idea for this task comes from a research paper

       İ. Çınar and M. Koklu. Identification of rice varieties using machine learning algorithms. Journal of Agricultural Sciences, 28(2):307–325, 2022. doi: 10.15832/ankutbd.862482.
       https://dergipark.org.tr/en/download/article-file/1513632

The numeric feature data is processed from images of rice grains. We got this images from Koklus website
       https://www.muratkoklu.com/datasets/vtdhnd09.php
This website has 15 000 photos for five different rice types: 75 000 photos in total. In this project we randomly select 100 photo from Arborio, Basmati and Jasmine photo pools: 300 photos in total.

We make explore the data with boxplots, histograms, scatter plot and, PCA. Then we train k nearest neigbours, random forest and mlp models and search for best hyperparameters for them. We do this by repeated cross validation: 5folds and 3repetitions. Then we evaluated the models with nested cross validation.

The result were quite promising even with the small amount of data we got over ninety precent accuracy score for predicting. This could be fortold even in the beginnig of the project when we got disting clusters in the initial visual estimation of the data. KNN gave us the best result and was the fastes to perform. This was by far the best model

Discussion¶

Discuss you results

KNN performes the best. It is clearly the fastest and most accurate. Based on the PCA we can say the clusters were vey distinct. In that case KNN will work very well as it is clear that the same type of samples tend to be near eachother. Random forest was the second best but was the slowest. MLP (Multi-layer perceptrons) perforemed the worst.

The models generalize well to these rice types that we used for training. The rice typed wwere clearly different in shape so much so that it could be seen with the naked eye. There are many rice types in the world and the models might not perform as well if they are added to the mix. The models will propably perform pretty well if we use it to predict the same type of rice we used to train it.

We got better result on KNN, same types of result for random forest and worse result for MLP than in the original paper. In the original paper they seemd to get the same type result in accuracy for all different methodds. We can't compare our result to the ones in the paper as we have less samples. We propably got better result for KNN because we have less rice types that are more distict to each other.

Application that can classify different species of could be used to identify eddible plants. This could be used by hobbyist. Mushromes are especially hard to identify. Many toxic mushromes look like non toxic ones. This could be a good future research field. To make mushroom collecting safer for people.

Many of the methods I used here I was already familiar with. Only new thing for me was nested cross validation using skilearns methods and processing the photos. I had done nested cross validation manually before so it wasnät difficult. Processing the photos felt the most difficult as I had no previous experince in that sort of work. It felt quite tedious and I needed to be very careful to get all the values correctly. Also that part needed a lot on researching online to get it done. I feel I could
